Check logical integrity of data¶

A number of additional checks will be performed to see if the data is reasonable. Depending on the amount of data affected or the analysis that follows, we may decide to drop the rows or replace the values.

Test 1 Check if any entries have invalid dates (impossible)¶

In [21]:
# Convert the case_month column to datetime format and check for any invalid dates
# According to DATA.CDC.gov, the data should begin from 2020.01 
# And from the attached file, last updated date was 2022.10.06, check if any case_month was out of the range.
test_1 = []
for year_month in df['case_month']:
    (year, month) = year_month.split("-")
    if 2020 <= int(year) <= 2021:
        if 1 <= int(month) <= 12:
            pass
        else:
            test_1.append(year_month)
    elif int(year) == 2022:
        if 1 <= int(month) <= 10:
            pass
        else:
            test_1.append(year_month)
    else:
        test_1.append(year_month)
        
test_1 = df[df['case_month'].isin(test_1)]

if len(test_1) > 0:
    print(f'there are {len(test_1)} invalid case_month rows')
    print(test_1['case_month'].head())
else:
    print("All case_month formats are correct.")

2. Data Understanding: Data Quality Plan for the cleaned CSV file.¶

In this section we list all features and the observations and actions involving those features, as a step towards obtaining a cleaner dataset.

The initial list of issues as identified in the Yu-Feng-22200055-Data_Quality_Report_Initial_Findings.pdf:¶

  • Logical tests in part 1 had some failures which should be handled.
  • Special value ‘missing’ and 'unknown' appeared in many rows covering multiple features. Given that values of Unknown and Missing is also invalid as NAN value, convert these values to NAN value for further analysis.
  • Special negative values appears in 2 features. case_positive_specimen_interval & case_onset_interval. It indicates positive specific date/onset date is earlier than cdc case earliest date, which makes no sense.
  • Different scales used for similar features - Categorical features res_county & county_fips_code are measuring the same event and are using the same numerical mappings. One-to-one mapping needs to be picked for consistency.
  • Presence of outliers - There are a significant number of outliers present across a range of different features. They initially look implausible and will need to be investigated further.

Data Understanding: Data Quality Plan¶

A potential data quality plan lists all features and actions involving those features:

Conclusion¶

  • When displaying the most frequent county corresponding to the state, some columns of state ('GU', 'PR', 'VI') with only null values. Drop all these columns of res_state because it makes no sense if the state with no county inside. Then, when applying imputation, firstly replace null values of feature res_county with the most frequent res_county and then replace null values of feature county_fips_code with the most frequent county_fips_code accordingly.
  • Feature county_fips_code has a large cardinality of 1208.0, after deep diving, I found the value of cardinality is reasonable because the code of county represents a more detailed location

3. Exploring relationships between feature pairs:¶

Choose a subset of features you find promising and plot pairwise feature interactions (e.g., continuous-continuous feature plot or continuous-categorical plots or correlation plots). Explain your choices.¶

The features that I will look at for pairwise feature interaction are the following continuous features:

  • case_positive_specimen_interval
  • case_onset_interval

and the following categorical features VS 'death_yn':

  • case_month
  • age_group
  • race
  • symptom_status
  • underlying_conditions_yn

The choices here I based on the idea that these particular features would be strong markers to track cases, deaths, and trends of COVID-19 in the United States, as also discussed based on plots in the Yu-Feng-22200055-Data_Quality_Report_Initial_Findings.pdf.

    • I do see a significant drop in the likelihood of death cases outcome if time interval between tests for the positive case and time interval between for the onset case increased. This is as expected and which means the virus is very serious and deadly.
  • Continuous vs Categorical
    • There was a strong association between the characteristics of the month of occurrence, age group, race and underlying symptom profile of the cases and the deaths.

New feature 3¶

  • A new column 'time_diff' is created based on the difference between two time intervals in the dataframe.
  • The column is then categorized as 'same', 'before', or 'after' based on the time difference, and the resulting value counts are printed.

df['time_diff'] = df['case_positive_specimen_interval'] - df['case_onset_interval']
df['time_diff'] = np.where(df['time_diff'] == 0, 'same', np.where(df['time_diff'] > 0, 'after', 'before'))
df['time_diff'] = df['time_diff'].astype('category')
